<ArticleLayout
  title="Outdoor Entertaining Area Setup: What to Plan Before Buying Extra Furniture and Accessories"
  description="Plan an outdoor entertaining area for Australian patios, balconies and backyards with practical checks for seating, serving space, shade, storage and barbecue layout."
  category="Outdoor & Garden"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/outdoor-garden.webp"
  imageAlt="An Australian patio set up for outdoor entertaining with seating, plants and natural light"
>
  <p>
    Outdoor entertaining often starts with a simple idea: a few people outside,
    somewhere to sit, a spot for food and enough shade to make the space usable.
    Then the extras begin to gather: spare chairs, folding tables, serving
    trolleys, cushions, lanterns, rugs, planters, covers and barbecue accessories.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bought one at a time, those extras can make a patio, balcony or courtyard
    feel busy even when no one is visiting. The useful test is whether each item
    improves normal outdoor use as well as the occasional larger gathering.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to plan before buying extra furniture and
    accessories for an outdoor entertaining area in an Australian home.
  </p>

  <h2>Start With the Type of Entertaining You Actually Do</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying extra furniture or accessories, think about the way people
    usually gather in your outdoor area.
  </p>
  <p>The space may need to support:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Casual weekend lunches.</li>
    <li>Family dinners outside.</li>
    <li>A few friends sitting around a table.</li>
    <li>Barbecue meals.</li>
    <li>Coffee or drinks outdoors.</li>
    <li>Kids moving between indoor and outdoor spaces.</li>
    <li>A relaxed lounge area.</li>
    <li>A balcony catch-up for two or three people.</li>
    <li>Occasional larger gatherings.</li>
    <li>Quiet everyday use when no one is visiting.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This matters because buying for the biggest possible gathering can make the
    space less useful every day. If most outdoor use is two to four people, a
    large collection of folding furniture may not need to live outside
    permanently. If outdoor meals happen often, serving space and storage may
    matter more than decorative extras.
  </p>
  <p>
    Buy for the common use first, then plan flexible extras for the occasional
    larger day.
  </p>

  <h2>Separate Everyday Setup From Occasional Extras</h2>
  <p>
    A practical outdoor entertaining area usually has two layers: the everyday
    setup and the occasional extras.
  </p>
  <p>The everyday setup may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A dining table or small outdoor table.</li>
    <li>Regular seating.</li>
    <li>A barbecue or outdoor cooking area.</li>
    <li>A lounge chair or sofa.</li>
    <li>A shade option.</li>
    <li>A small storage spot.</li>
    <li>A few planters.</li>
    <li>Basic serving space.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Occasional extras may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Folding chairs.</li>
    <li>Extra cushions.</li>
    <li>A temporary table.</li>
    <li>A serving trolley.</li>
    <li>Outdoor trays.</li>
    <li>Extra shade.</li>
    <li>Portable lighting.</li>
    <li>A gazebo or temporary shelter.</li>
    <li>Larger serving items.</li>
    <li>Outdoor games or kids' items.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The mistake is leaving occasional extras in the everyday layout. If folding
    chairs, spare tables and extra accessories are always visible, the space may
    feel cluttered even when it is not being used for entertaining.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the Entertaining Zone</h2>
  <p>
    Outdoor entertaining needs movement space as much as furniture space. People
    need to sit, stand, carry plates, move between the kitchen and barbecue,
    access bins, reach storage and move around without constantly shifting
    chairs.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying extras, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The main outdoor area width and depth.</li>
    <li>Dining table footprint.</li>
    <li>Chair pull-out space.</li>
    <li>Lounge seating footprint.</li>
    <li>Barbecue zone.</li>
    <li>Walkways between kitchen, table and barbecue.</li>
    <li>Door and sliding-door opening space.</li>
    <li>Gate and side access.</li>
    <li>Storage access.</li>
    <li>Space for a temporary table or trolley.</li>
    <li>Space for people standing, not just sitting.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A spare table may seem useful until it blocks the main path from the
    kitchen. Extra chairs may help guests sit down but make the area difficult
    to move through. A trolley may add serving space but still needs somewhere
    sensible to park.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the space already includes a table, compare the layout with the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-dining-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-furniture/">outdoor dining area setup guide</a>{" "}
    before adding extra furniture.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan the Flow From Kitchen to Outdoor Area</h2>
  <p>
    Outdoor entertaining usually involves repeated trips between the kitchen,
    barbecue, table, bin and storage area. A good setup makes those trips
    simpler.
  </p>
  <p>Check the path between:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Kitchen door.</li>
    <li>Barbecue.</li>
    <li>Dining table.</li>
    <li>Lounge seating.</li>
    <li>Serving surface.</li>
    <li>Rubbish or bin area.</li>
    <li>Outdoor storage.</li>
    <li>Indoor fridge or pantry.</li>
    <li>Side gate or outdoor access path.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This is not about creating a commercial entertaining zone. It is about
    avoiding awkward movement. If people carrying food have to squeeze behind
    chairs, step around planters or move through the cooking area, the layout
    may need adjustment before buying more accessories.
  </p>
  <p>
    For outdoor cooking layouts, link planning back to the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/barbecue-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-outdoor-cooking-gear/">barbecue area setup guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide Whether You Need More Seating or Better Seating</h2>
  <p>
    Extra chairs are often the first outdoor entertaining purchase, but more
    seats are not always the answer.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying extra seating, ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>How many people use the space most weeks?</li>
    <li>How often do larger groups visit?</li>
    <li>Where will extra chairs be stored?</li>
    <li>Can existing indoor chairs be used occasionally?</li>
    <li>Would benches, stools or folding chairs suit the space?</li>
    <li>Do the extra seats block walkways?</li>
    <li>Will people actually sit in all the positions available?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A compact outdoor area may work better with fewer comfortable seats and a
    flexible spare chair plan. A larger patio may support a dining setting and
    separate lounge seating. A balcony may only suit two regular chairs and one
    occasional stool.
  </p>
  <p>
    For lounge-focused setups, compare seating choices with the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-lounge-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-seating/">outdoor lounge seating guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan Tables, Trolleys and Serving Surfaces</h2>
  <p>
    Outdoor entertaining often fails when there is nowhere to put food, drinks,
    plates or serving items. The solution is not always a larger dining table.
  </p>
  <p>Possible serving options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A small side table.</li>
    <li>A folding table used only when needed.</li>
    <li>A serving trolley.</li>
    <li>A barbecue side shelf.</li>
    <li>A storage cabinet with a usable top.</li>
    <li>A tray carried from the kitchen.</li>
    <li>A small outdoor bench or console.</li>
    <li>A coffee table in a lounge area.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the surface blocks movement.</li>
    <li>Whether it can be cleaned easily.</li>
    <li>Whether it stores away when not in use.</li>
    <li>Whether it is close enough to the table or barbecue.</li>
    <li>Whether it becomes clutter when not entertaining.</li>
    <li>Whether it suits the outdoor surface.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A trolley can be useful if the path is clear and storage exists. A folding
    table can help occasionally but may become annoying if it has nowhere to go.
    A side table can be enough for small gatherings without taking over the
    area.
  </p>

  <h2>Think About Shade Before Adding More Furniture</h2>
  <p>
    Shade can affect where people sit, where food is placed and whether the
    outdoor area feels usable at different times of day.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying entertaining extras, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where shade falls during the usual entertaining time.</li>
    <li>Whether the dining table is shaded.</li>
    <li>Whether the lounge area is shaded.</li>
    <li>Whether a barbecue or serving zone competes with the shade position.</li>
    <li>Whether an umbrella base blocks a walkway.</li>
    <li>Whether temporary shade needs storage.</li>
    <li>Whether shade products can open and close properly.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not treat shade as the final accessory after furniture has already been
    bought. A large umbrella or gazebo can change the entire layout.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader shade checks, use the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-shade-setup-for-patios-and-backyards-what-to-check-before-buying/">outdoor shade setup guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid Overloading the Area With Accessories</h2>
  <p>
    Outdoor accessories can make the space feel finished, but they can also add
    clutter.
  </p>
  <p>Common extras include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Outdoor cushions.</li>
    <li>Throws.</li>
    <li>Lanterns.</li>
    <li>Outdoor rugs.</li>
    <li>Planters.</li>
    <li>Side tables.</li>
    <li>Trays.</li>
    <li>Tableware.</li>
    <li>Decorative bowls.</li>
    <li>Storage baskets.</li>
    <li>Outdoor games.</li>
    <li>Portable speakers.</li>
    <li>Tablecloths and placemats.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Before buying accessories, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the item has a regular purpose.</li>
    <li>Whether it needs storage.</li>
    <li>Whether it can stay outside.</li>
    <li>Whether it makes cleaning harder.</li>
    <li>Whether it competes with furniture.</li>
    <li>Whether it suits the weather exposure.</li>
    <li>Whether it will still look useful when no one is visiting.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A small number of useful extras will usually work better than a large
    collection of decorative pieces that need to be moved, cleaned or stored.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan Storage Before Buying More Entertaining Gear</h2>
  <p>Outdoor entertaining extras need somewhere to live.</p>
  <p>Storage may be needed for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Folding chairs.</li>
    <li>Outdoor cushions.</li>
    <li>Furniture covers.</li>
    <li>Serving trays.</li>
    <li>Tablecloths.</li>
    <li>Outdoor tableware.</li>
    <li>Barbecue tools.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths.</li>
    <li>Kids' outdoor items.</li>
    <li>Temporary shade accessories.</li>
    <li>Outdoor games.</li>
    <li>Spare pots or plant supplies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Before buying, decide whether these items will be stored:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>In an outdoor storage box.</li>
    <li>In a garage.</li>
    <li>In a laundry cupboard.</li>
    <li>In a garden shed.</li>
    <li>In a kitchen cabinet.</li>
    <li>Under a bench or seat.</li>
    <li>In a weather-protected cabinet.</li>
    <li>In a portable tub used only for gatherings.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If storage is already tight, avoid buying accessories that need bulky
    storage for only occasional use.
  </p>
  <p>
    For storage planning, use the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-storage-for-small-australian-backyards-what-to-plan-before-buying/">small backyard outdoor storage guide</a>{" "}
    and the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-storage-ideas-australian-patios-balconies-gardens/">outdoor storage ideas guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider the Reset After Guests Leave</h2>
  <p>
    A good entertaining setup should be easy to reset. If everything has to be
    carried around the house, dried, folded, covered or stored awkwardly, the
    setup may become too much effort.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>How long will this take to pack away?</li>
    <li>Where does each item go afterwards?</li>
    <li>Can one person reset the area?</li>
    <li>Does the furniture need to be covered?</li>
    <li>Do cushions need to come inside?</li>
    <li>Does the floor need to be cleared for normal use?</li>
    <li>Will the items be left outside because storage is annoying?</li>
    <li>Does the space still work the next day?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A simple reset matters more than a highly styled setup. The easier the area
    is to return to normal, the more likely it is to be used regularly.
  </p>

  <h2>Outdoor Entertaining on Balconies</h2>
  <p>Balcony entertaining needs careful restraint because space is limited.</p>
  <p>Before buying extras for a balcony, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Balcony depth.</li>
    <li>Door opening space.</li>
    <li>Chair movement.</li>
    <li>Table size.</li>
    <li>Rail and view lines.</li>
    <li>Wind exposure.</li>
    <li>Storage space.</li>
    <li>Whether folding items have somewhere to go.</li>
    <li>Whether plants already use the best edges.</li>
    <li>Whether guests can move without shifting furniture.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A balcony may work best with a small table, two regular chairs, one
    occasional stool and a tray-based serving system. Large extras can quickly
    turn a balcony into storage rather than usable space.
  </p>

  <h2>Outdoor Entertaining in Courtyards</h2>
  <p>
    Courtyards can feel intimate and useful, but they can also become crowded
    because walls define the space tightly.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying extras for a courtyard, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Wall-to-wall dimensions.</li>
    <li>Door and gate positions.</li>
    <li>Existing planters.</li>
    <li>Furniture layout.</li>
    <li>Shade pattern.</li>
    <li>Storage access.</li>
    <li>Whether sound and activity carry into nearby rooms or neighbouring areas.</li>
    <li>Whether the courtyard looks crowded from inside.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A courtyard may suit one clear entertaining zone rather than multiple small
    furniture groups. Grouping planters and storage neatly can help the space
    feel calmer.
  </p>
  <p>
    If planters are part of the setup, check the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/balcony-and-courtyard-garden-setup-what-to-plan-before-buying-pots-and-planters/">balcony and courtyard garden setup guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Outdoor Entertaining on Patios and Decks</h2>
  <p>Patios and decks may have more space, but the layout still needs planning.</p>
  <p>Before buying extras, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether dining and lounge zones overlap.</li>
    <li>Whether the barbecue has enough room.</li>
    <li>Whether chairs block doors.</li>
    <li>Whether shade reaches the main seating.</li>
    <li>Whether the deck or patio surface suits the furniture.</li>
    <li>Whether outdoor rugs, tables or trolleys create awkward clutter.</li>
    <li>Whether garden access stays clear.</li>
    <li>Whether the setup looks balanced from indoors.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A patio can often support a dining zone and a separate lounge zone, but only
    if there is enough space between them. If the area is smaller, it may be
    better to choose one main purpose and keep extras flexible.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose Flexible Extras Carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Flexible furniture and accessories can help, but only if they are genuinely
    easy to use.
  </p>
  <p>Examples include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Folding chairs.</li>
    <li>Stackable chairs.</li>
    <li>Nesting tables.</li>
    <li>Lightweight side tables.</li>
    <li>Serving trays.</li>
    <li>Portable shade.</li>
    <li>Storage benches.</li>
    <li>Modular seating.</li>
    <li>Portable tubs for entertaining supplies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the item is easy to move.</li>
    <li>Whether it folds or stacks neatly.</li>
    <li>Whether it has a clear storage place.</li>
    <li>Whether it suits the intended everyday use.</li>
    <li>Whether it will be used often enough.</li>
    <li>Whether it solves a real layout problem.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Flexible products can reduce clutter, but they still take up space
    somewhere.
  </p>

  <h2>Think About the View From Inside</h2>
  <p>
    Outdoor entertaining areas are often visible from the kitchen, dining room
    or living area.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying extra furniture or accessories, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the setup looks crowded from inside.</li>
    <li>Whether spare chairs are always visible.</li>
    <li>Whether covers and storage boxes dominate the view.</li>
    <li>Whether planters soften or crowd the area.</li>
    <li>Whether a trolley looks like permanent clutter.</li>
    <li>Whether the colour and scale suit the outdoor surfaces.</li>
    <li>Whether the area still looks calm when not being used.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The outdoor area does not need to look styled all the time, but it should
    not feel like a holding zone for occasional party gear.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid Buying the Whole Setup at Once</h2>
  <p>Outdoor entertaining areas often improve when they are built in stages.</p>
  <p>A staged approach may be:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Set up the main table or seating first.</li>
    <li>Check movement and access.</li>
    <li>Add one useful serving surface.</li>
    <li>Plan shade where it is actually needed.</li>
    <li>Add storage for cushions and accessories.</li>
    <li>Add extras only after using the space a few times.</li>
    <li>Remove items that do not earn their place.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This avoids buying items that look useful in theory but do not fit the
    actual flow of the home.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Take</h2>
  <p>
    Outdoor entertaining works better when the everyday layout comes first and
    occasional extras come second. A patio, balcony or courtyard should still be
    easy to use when no one is visiting. If spare furniture, serving items and
    accessories make the space crowded every day, the arrangement is probably
    overbuilt.
  </p>
  <p>
    For many Australian homes, the practical answer is a clear main area, a
    small amount of flexible seating, one useful serving surface, sensible shade
    and storage that makes reset easy. Buy items because they solve a repeated
    problem, not because they might be handy one day.
  </p>
  <p>
    The aim is not a perfect entertaining space. It is an outdoor area that can
    handle guests without becoming difficult to live with the rest of the week.
  </p>

  <h2>Before You Buy Checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying extra outdoor entertaining furniture or accessories, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>How the outdoor area is used most weeks.</li>
    <li>How often larger gatherings actually happen.</li>
    <li>Whether the everyday setup already works.</li>
    <li>Whether extra furniture needs storage.</li>
    <li>Whether chair movement and walkways stay clear.</li>
    <li>Whether there is a practical path from kitchen to table.</li>
    <li>Whether the barbecue area has enough space.</li>
    <li>Whether serving surfaces are needed.</li>
    <li>Whether shade reaches the main seating area.</li>
    <li>Whether temporary shade needs storage.</li>
    <li>Whether cushions and covers have a clear home.</li>
    <li>Whether accessories will add clutter.</li>
    <li>Whether the setup can be reset easily.</li>
    <li>Whether the outdoor area still looks reasonable from inside.</li>
    <li>Whether each item solves a real problem.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
  <h3>Buying for the Biggest Possible Gathering</h3>
  <p>
    Furniture for rare events can make the outdoor area less useful every day.
  </p>

  <h3>Forgetting Storage for Occasional Extras</h3>
  <p>
    Folding chairs, trolleys, covers and temporary shade still need somewhere
    to go.
  </p>

  <h3>Adding Accessories Before Fixing Layout Problems</h3>
  <p>
    Cushions, rugs and decorative pieces will not solve poor movement, crowding
    or lack of serving space.
  </p>

  <h3>Blocking the Kitchen-to-Table Path</h3>
  <p>Outdoor entertaining involves repeated movement. Keep the main path clear.</p>

  <h3>Leaving Occasional Gear Outside Permanently</h3>
  <p>
    If occasional items stay out all the time, the space may feel cluttered even
    when it is not being used.
  </p>

  <h2>How This Connects With the Rest of the Outdoor Area</h2>
  <p>
    Outdoor entertaining brings together dining, lounge seating, shade,
    barbecue planning, garden layout and storage. Each decision affects the
    others.
  </p>
  <p>
    If meals are the focus, start with the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-dining-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-furniture/">outdoor dining area setup guide</a>.
    If relaxed seating matters more, use the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-lounge-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-seating/">outdoor lounge seating guide</a>.
    If cooking is central to the setup, compare the layout with the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/barbecue-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-outdoor-cooking-gear/">barbecue area setup guide</a>.
    Then check shade and storage using the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-shade-setup-for-patios-and-backyards-what-to-check-before-buying/">outdoor shade setup guide</a>{" "}
    and the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-storage-for-small-australian-backyards-what-to-plan-before-buying/">small backyard outdoor storage guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
  <p>
    An outdoor entertaining area does not need to be large or heavily styled to
    work well. It needs a clear layout, enough room to move, practical serving
    space, shade where it matters and somewhere for occasional items to go
    afterwards.
  </p>
  <p>
    Plan around the way the area is used most weeks. A leaner arrangement that
    resets easily will usually be more useful than a crowded outdoor area filled
    with items kept for occasional guests.
  </p>

